# using LEFT JOIN

query = """
SELECT 
    T.yearID, 
    T.teamID, 
    T.franchID, 
    T.W AS wins, 
    T.G AS games_played, 
    SUM(S.salary) AS total_payroll,
    (T.W * 100.0 / T.G) AS win_percentage
FROM 
    Teams AS T
LEFT JOIN 
    Salaries AS S 
ON 
    T.teamID = S.teamID AND T.yearID = S.yearID
WHERE 
    T.yearID BETWEEN 1990 AND 2014
GROUP BY 
    T.yearID, T.teamID;
"""
team_data = pd.read_sql(query, conn)

team_data['total_payroll'] = team_data['total_payroll'].fillna(0)

# (c) Write up for problem 1 - Total Payroll and Winning Percentage

# My Explanation of the Code:
# The SQL query will get the total payroll and winning percentage for each baseball team, year by year, between 1990 and 2014.
# I combined data from the Teams and Salaries tables based on the team ID and year, using LEFT JOIN. 
# I get every team and year from the Teams table, regardless of whether there's matching data in the Salaries table. 
# If a team is missing salary data for a given year, the total_payroll will show up as NULL.
# I’m using columns yearID, teamID, and franchID to identify the team and year.
# I’m using SUM(S.salary) to add up all salaries and get the total payroll for each team per year.
# For winning percentage, I did (T.W * 100.0 / T.G), where T.W is the number of wins and T.G is the total games played. 
# I used 100.0 instead of 100 to make sure it treats the numbers as floats, which keeps the decimal places and avoids rounding.
# To handle these missing values, I used fillna(0) in Pandas. This replaces any NULL values in the total_payroll column with 0.

from scipy.stats import linregress

team_data['period'] = pd.cut(team_data['yearID'], 
                             bins=[1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009, 2014],
                             labels=['1990-1994', '1995-1999', '2000-2004', '2005-2009', '2010-2014'])

period_summary = team_data.groupby(['period', 'teamID']).agg({
    'total_payroll': 'mean',
    'win_percentage': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

periods = period_summary['period'].unique()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

for i, period in enumerate(periods, 1):
    
    data = period_summary[period_summary['period'] == period].dropna(subset=['total_payroll', 'win_percentage'])
    
    plt.subplot(2, 3, i)
    plt.scatter(data['total_payroll'], data['win_percentage'], alpha=0.7, color='blue')
    
    # Check if there are enough points to fit a regression line
    if len(data) > 1:
        slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(data['total_payroll'], data['win_percentage'])
        regression_line = slope * data['total_payroll'] + intercept
        plt.plot(data['total_payroll'], regression_line, color='red', label='Regression Line')
        
        # Add the regression line equation as text on the plot
        equation_text = f'y = {slope:.4f}x + {intercept:.2f}'
        plt.text(0.05, 0.90, equation_text, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, fontsize=10, color='red', 
                 bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5))
    
    # Label all teams on the plot with different colors for Oakland A's
    for idx, row in data.iterrows():
        if row['teamID'] == 'OAK':
            # Oakland A's in dark green
            plt.annotate(row['teamID'], 
                         (row['total_payroll'], row['win_percentage']),
                         textcoords="offset points",
                         xytext=(5, -5),
                         ha='center',
                         fontsize=8, color='darkgreen')
        else:
            # Other teams in dark blue
            plt.annotate(row['teamID'], 
                         (row['total_payroll'], row['win_percentage']),
                         textcoords="offset points",
                         xytext=(5, -5),
                         ha='center',
                         fontsize=8, color='darkblue')
    
    plt.xlabel('Mean Payroll (in $)')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Winning Percentage')
    plt.title(f'Mean Winning % vs. Payroll ({period})')
    plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# This gives me the equation y=mx+b, where y is the winning percentage and x is the payroll.
# I plotted the regression line in red with plt.plot(). 
# This line helps show whether there’s a positive or negative relationship between payroll and winning percentage in each period.
# I used plt.text() to add the regression equation to each plot. 
# The position (0.05, 0.90) places the text in the top-left corner of the plot.
# I set transform=plt.gca().transAxes to position the text relative to the plot area, not the data points.
# I included a white background box with bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5) to make the equation readable.

# I added axis labels (plt.xlabel() and plt.ylabel()).
# This shows that x-axis represents the mean payroll and the y-axis represents the mean winning percentage.
# Each subplot has a title indicating the period it represents. 
# The plt.legend() call adds a legend that labels the regression line, which helps interpret the red line as the regression line.

# Each period shows whether there is a positive or negative trend, as indicated by the slope of the red regression line.

import pandas as pd

# Assuming 'team_data' DataFrame contains 'yearID' and 'total_payroll' columns

# Calculate the mean and standard deviation of payroll for each year
yearly_stats = team_data.groupby('yearID')['total_payroll'].agg(['mean', 'std']).reset_index()
yearly_stats.rename(columns={'mean': 'avg_payroll', 'std': 'std_payroll'}, inplace=True)

# Merge the statistics back with the original data on 'yearID'
team_data = team_data.merge(yearly_stats, on='yearID')

# Calculate the standardized payroll
team_data['standardized_payroll'] = (team_data['total_payroll'] - team_data['avg_payroll']) / team_data['std_payroll']

# Display the first few rows to verify the calculation
print(team_data[['yearID', 'teamID', 'total_payroll', 'avg_payroll', 'std_payroll', 'standardized_payroll']].head())

# (c) My explanation of the code-

# The standardized_payroll column in my dataset adjusts each team’s payroll by comparing it to the average payroll
# and standard deviation for that year. 
# I also disabled scientific notation so the numbers are easier to read, showing up in regular decimal format.
# Calculating Yearly Stats:
# I grouped the data by year to find the average (avg_payroll) and standard deviation (std_payroll) for payroll in each year. 
# This sets up the values I need to standardize payrolls across years.
# I merged these yearly statistics back into the main team_data DataFrame.
# Now, each row has its corresponding year's average and standard deviation, making it easy to calculate the standardized payroll.
# Standardizing the Payroll:
# Using the formula (total_payroll−avg_payroll)/std_payroll, I calculated the standardized_payroll for each team and year. 
# This new value shows how each team’s payroll compares to the rest of the league for that year.
# I have shown the output is shown as regular decimal numbers, which is easier to interpret when comparing values.
# By standardizing the payrolls, I can now compare spending more effectively across different years, 
# since it adjusts for yearly changes in average payrolls.

team_data['period'] = pd.cut(team_data['yearID'], 
                             bins=[1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009, 2014],
                             labels=['1990-1994', '1995-1999', '2000-2004', '2005-2009', '2010-2014'])

period_summary = team_data.groupby(['period', 'teamID']).agg({
    'standardized_payroll': 'mean',
    'win_percentage': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

periods = period_summary['period'].unique()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

for i, period in enumerate(periods, 1):
    # Filter data for the current period and drop any rows with missing values
    data = period_summary[period_summary['period'] == period].dropna(subset=['standardized_payroll', 'win_percentage'])
    
    # Scatter plot for the current period
    plt.subplot(2, 3, i)
    plt.scatter(data['standardized_payroll'], data['win_percentage'], alpha=0.7, color='blue')
    
    # Check if there are enough points to fit a regression line
    if len(data) > 1:
        slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(data['standardized_payroll'], data['win_percentage'])
        regression_line = slope * data['standardized_payroll'] + intercept
        plt.plot(data['standardized_payroll'], regression_line, color='red', label='Regression Line')
        
        # Add the regression line equation as text on the plot
        equation_text = f'y = {slope:.4f}x + {intercept:.2f}'
        plt.text(0.05, 0.90, equation_text, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, fontsize=10, color='red', 
                 bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5))
    
    # Annotate all teams on the plot
    for idx, row in data.iterrows():
        plt.annotate(row['teamID'], 
                     (row['standardized_payroll'], row['win_percentage']),
                     textcoords="offset points",
                     xytext=(5, -5),
                     ha='center',
                     fontsize=8, color='darkblue')  

    # Labels and title
    plt.xlabel('Standardized Payroll')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Winning Percentage')
    plt.title(f'Mean Winning % vs. Standardized Payroll ({period})')
    plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

filtered_data = team_data.dropna(subset=['standardized_payroll', 'win_percentage'])

# Define colors for different decades
colors = {
    '1990s': 'blue',
    '2000s': 'green',
    '2010s': 'purple'
}

# Add a new column to categorize years into decades for color coding
filtered_data['decade'] = pd.cut(filtered_data['yearID'],
                                 bins=[1989, 1999, 2009, 2019],
                                 labels=['1990s', '2000s', '2010s'])

# Plot data points with color coding for each decade
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

for decade, color in colors.items():
    # Filter data for the current decade
    decade_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['decade'] == decade]
    plt.scatter(decade_data['standardized_payroll'], decade_data['win_percentage'], alpha=0.6, color=color, label=decade)

# Calculate and plot the regression line across all data points
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(filtered_data['standardized_payroll'], filtered_data['win_percentage'])
regression_line = slope * filtered_data['standardized_payroll'] + intercept
plt.plot(filtered_data['standardized_payroll'], regression_line, color='red', label='Regression Line')

# Add the regression equation as text on the plot
equation_text = f'y = {intercept:.2f} + {slope:.2f} * x'
plt.text(0.05, 0.90, equation_text, transform=plt.gca().transAxes, fontsize=10, color='red', 
         bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5))

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel('Standardized Payroll')
plt.ylabel('Winning Percentage')
plt.title('Winning Percentage vs. Standardized Payroll (All Periods Combined)')

# Add a legend to distinguish decades and the regression line
plt.legend(title='Decade', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)

plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.cm as cm

# Calculate expected winning percentage based on the regression equation
filtered_data['expected_win_pct'] = intercept + slope * filtered_data['standardized_payroll']

# Calculate spending efficiency as the difference between actual and expected winning percentages
filtered_data['spending_efficiency'] = filtered_data['win_percentage'] - filtered_data['expected_win_pct']

# Get a list of all unique team IDs from the filtered data
all_teams = filtered_data['teamID'].unique()

# Create a color map with enough colors for all teams
colors = plt.cm.get_cmap('tab20', len(all_teams))
team_colors = {team_id: colors(i) for i, team_id in enumerate(all_teams)}

# Plotting Spending Efficiency over Time for all teams with unique colors
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

# Loop over each team to plot their data points
for team_id in all_teams:
    team_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['teamID'] == team_id]
    plt.scatter(team_data['yearID'], team_data['spending_efficiency'], 
                color=team_colors[team_id], label=team_id, alpha=0.6, s=30)

# Add labels and title
plt.axhline(0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)  # Reference line at zero
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Spending Efficiency (Actual - Expected Win %)')
plt.title('Spending Efficiency Over Time for All Teams')

# Manually create the legend with all team colors outside the plot
handles = [plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor=team_colors[team_id], markersize=6) for team_id in all_teams]

filtered_data['expected_win_pct'] = intercept + slope * filtered_data['standardized_payroll']

# Calculate spending efficiency as the difference between actual and expected winning percentages
filtered_data['spending_efficiency'] = filtered_data['win_percentage'] - filtered_data['expected_win_pct']

# Filter data for the specific teams: OAK, BOS, NYA, ATL, TBA
teams_of_interest = ['OAK', 'BOS', 'NYA', 'ATL', 'TBA']
team_data_filtered = filtered_data[filtered_data['teamID'].isin(teams_of_interest)]

# Plot spending efficiency over time for each team
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

for team in teams_of_interest:
    team_data = team_data_filtered[team_data_filtered['teamID'] == team]
    plt.plot(team_data['yearID'], team_data['spending_efficiency'], label=team)
